        <td  bgcolor="#FFFFFF" width="100%" valign="top"><font color="#08599C">
         <b>Author:&nbsp;<a class=doctorLink href="mailto:&#97;&#108;&#101;&#120;&#97;&#110;&#100;&#114;&#97;&#45;&#99;&#97;&#114;&#100;&#111;&#115;&#111;&#64;&#115;&#97;&#112;&#111;&#46;&#112;&#116;?subject=Time for a schedule change?">Alexandra</a> </b><br>
         <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
           <tr>
             <td><font color="#08599C"><b>Date:&nbsp;</b></font></td>
             <td><DIV DIR="ltr"><font color="#08599C"><b>02-11-2005 10:44</b></font></DIV></td>
           </tr>
         </table>
         <br>
      This is the main point on a piece of news on Eurosport about the need to shorten the Tennis season in order to protect the health and physicall well being of the players and, as a result, the sport and the spectacle in itself.<br />
I, for my part agree with most of what is said (excep with the limit on Masters Series tournaments and the banning of top-players from entering lower-tier events - because every one should have a right to choose where they want to play).<br />
Here is the article below.<br />
<br />
'Recent winners Marat Safin and Tim Henman joined Roger Federer, Rafael Nadal, Lleyton Hewitt, Andre Agassi, Richard Gasquet, Carlos Moya and Gael Monfils in pulling out of the biggest indoor tennis tournament of the season.<br />
<br />
Only Andy Roddick, last week's Lyon champion, who has criticised the Association of Tennis Professionals calendar, remains from the star name exodus.<br />
<br />
"Something has to be changed," Pioline told reporters in south-west Paris on Monday.<br />
<br />
"We're waiting for a sign from the ATP. The top tournaments like the Masters Series events need to be highlighted and protected."<br />
<br />
Masters Series organisers long since gave up on changing the faces on the posters adorning metro stations and boulevards.<br />
<br />
"We can't change the prize money or the venue at the last minute," said Pioline.<br />
<br />
L'Equipe ran an article on Monday, stating what the sport's associations: ATP, Women's Tennis Association and International Tennis Federation, could do to ease the scheduling dilemma.<br />
<br />
The French daily sports newspaper noted players should not compete in more than three tournaments per month with events on the same continent each week.<br />
<br />
Tennis balls should be standardised worldwide according to the surface and best-of-five set finals outside of the four major championships should be scrapped.<br />
<br />
The newspaper also proposed a limit of Masters Series tournaments to five per season and top-ranked players banned from entering lower-tier events.<br />
<br />
Certainly some of L'Equipe's points are well made, but the players - Greg Rusedski among them - say not much can be done about it.<br />
<br />
"Tennis nowadays is so much more physical and so much harder every match you have to play that you're going to get a lot more injuries," said Rusedski, a first round victor on Monday.<br />
<br />
"But, you know, I think they've already shortened the season quite a bit. It's kind of hard to figure out a way to shorten it again, to be honest with you."<br />
<br />
As an example, French Open champion Nadal has played in 23 tournaments taking 11 inter-continental flights for his ATP-high 89 matches in 2005.'<br />
<br />
Eurosport - James Buddell in Paris - 31/10/2005<br />
<br />
Link: <a class=doctorLink href="http://www.eurosport.com/home/pages/v4/l0/s57/e7345/sport_lng0_spo57_evt7345_sto784493.shtml">http://www.eurosport.com/home/pages/v4/l0/s57/e7345/sport_lng0_spo57_evt7345_sto784493.shtml</a></font></tt><p>
